,Not Recommended,266840,22539175,"Posted: 20 April, 2016",all,Shroom King,"Bought this game again to re-experience a game I absolutely loved as a kid, it was easily one of my favorite RTS' at the time. So going back to it after all these years would be great right?Well...no. Unfortunately the game hasn't aged all that well. At all. Gameplay is far slower and clunkier than I remember it being, which is strange since it feels slower than Age of Empires 2 (Which has aged far better than this game).The graphics arn't stylistic enough to still look good, it looks more like Nintendo 64 level than anything that was the standard at the time. While the environments and buildings tend to look pretty good, the units just look fairly lackluster. Gameplay is just so god damned slowed, even the battles feel so slow and clunky you would think you were running it at the slowest speed possible. In concept units all have counters for one another, some units are better are killing certain units than others, but unless you're an expert at micromanaging in practice it just proves completely worthless.Even when I tried micromanaging my units according to their counters, combat was still slower than molasses and just felt overall unsatisfying. Defenses feel almost worthless in this game as well, no matter how well constructed your base defenses are simple infantry can just break through it in no time. The myth units are still overpowered as ever, even if you counter them with heroes.Also the new expansion doesn't add anything particularly worthwhile. The idea is awesome! Ancient chinese units and myths all integrated into a new faction! In practice, it's nothing special at all. It feels like Greek-Lite more than anything. The campaign it adds is just so bland and uninteresting as well. Speaking of, the main campaign of the story is bland and uninteresting overall, with only a few levels that really rise up to being great (Arkantos' Dream being the most prominent). All of it boils down to ""Build up base, take down X."" with very little variation or story bits in the middle.While this would normally be nothing to really complain about (since that's the core of an RTS afterall), the slow and uninteresting gameplay piled on top of that makes the Campaign feel like a complete and utter grind.The concept is still fantastic, but in practice it's really just not all that great a game. I've went back and played quite a few older RTS' and sadly AOM just doesn't hold up like its brothers and sisters of the time. I loved this game once, but going back and playing it? I can't really remember why I loved it."
