76561198071689614,Not Recommended,266840,16516387,"Posted: 18 June, 2015",all,Mystic Exarch,"The main problem with this game is that the enemy AI is poorly coded. They're not fun to play against because they build up tons of defense and an army. But they don't ever leave their base with their army. They use it to defend while they build a wonder. Once you build a wonder, you win the game in 10 minutes. So the AI strategy is to just rush a wonder while defending.Also there is a system in which you have 4 ages. Each age is comparable to a tier in other RTS games...it unlocks new technology and units. The way the game is balanced, advancing your ages faster is a massive advantage. So therefore the game is a rush to the final age and then the game actually starts for real.You can't really be agressive in this game because your army will get stomped by you opponent's towers and base, which have arrow attacks. You need siege weapons to damage buildings, but you don't get them until later on.So the gameplay basically becomes, focus on economy and building up resources for an hour while advancing through the ages as fast as you can. Rush a wonder, or build up an epic army and have one battle at the end of the game. It's very repetitive and doesn't inspire creativity, which is something integral to the RPG genre.Also this game is missing a HUGE feature. The ""a move"". Without it it's a huge pain to manage your units.This is compunded by the fact that the units are so tiny and there are oftentimes hundreds on the screen at once. I simply can't tell what's going on or if I am winning or not. You have to order your men to attack one unit at atime, which messes everything up because they get all gummed up trying to attack the same unit. But there's really nothing else you can do.I bought this game for real cheap on the summer sale. I can't reccomend it for the full price, though, which is why it gets a downvote."
,Not Recommended,266840,16455537,"Posted: 16 June, 2015",all,Blood Tears,"Age of Mythology. My childhood. The first RTS I ever played, and one of the first video games I sunk hours of my life into. This was a great game! But chancces are, if you're reading this review, you do not have nostalgia to fall back on. For me, seeing this game on sale was a no-brainer - I had to get it and replay it and recapture the magic.So after about 11 years, what is my impression? Well... if you've already played this game, and love it, go for it. But it definitely doesn't stand the test of time, for me. What was fun and groundbreaking and challenging 11 years ago has been repeated many times since in better games. So rather than posting a tired meme or ""PROSTAGOMA 10/10 LOL,"" here is a list of pros and cons for those who have never tried the game and actually want something substiantial to go on.Pros:*One of the only RTSes out there with a focus on ancient culture and the mythology that surrounds them. While other RTSes focus on realism or space exploration, AOM treats the myths of the acient Greeks, the Egyptians, the Norse, and the Atlanteans as if they were real. As a teenager playing this game, I learned a lot about these ancient cultures from this game. Oh, and there's the Atlanteans, because yeah.*Campaign does a decent job of going through all the civilizations and leading you on an adventure.* Mythical creatues will fight for you and destroy things.*God powers will destroy things.Cons:*Even remastered, the graphics are still not great. Which is fine, because it's old.* There are only four different cultures to play as. This is in opposition to pretty much every other RTS I've played, which have 10 at a minimum. It gets pretty boring after a while having to play the same cultures over and over. It would have been nice to add some from Asian or South America - there are tons of options they could have gone with.* It's honestly a step down from Age of Empires 2. It's like it took all the features in that game, and then cut out a bunch of stuff from each feature and then dumbed it down. Fewer cultures, fewer types of buildings, limits on how many buildings you can build so that your camps all end up looking the same. Even the maps are much more boring with less varied terrain. You can't convert enemy units or buildings, your farms stay there forever (which grantes is less annoying, but it still feels dumbed down). Fishing boats stay in place forever as well.* Because of this, there just isn't a lot to do. AI operates in the same way every time, there are only a few different buildings to build or units to create. Since you don't have a lot to build, every city looks the same.* Which is why most people used to focus on the multiplayer aspect of the game. Unfortunately, well, it's been 12 years. Everyone moved on. You can find better multiplayer communities elsewhere.* The campaign is, well, tedious. Rather than focusing on history, they focus on a bunch of stupid characters who barely have a personality. You don't really get a lot of time to build up encampments, and when you do it all goes away moving on to the next campaign, when you've suddenly forgotten all of the technology you learned.* Arkantos' piece of♥♥♥♥♥♥son. I hate that kid. He was the first video game character I ever wanted to see die.Anyway, if you like RTS games, there are a lot better ones you can buy. Age of Empires 2 came out 4 years before this one and yet still has more features. I haven't gotten to AoE III yet, but I'm guessing that would be even better. And this isn't counting the games like Civilization whose complexity blows this game out of the water. Basically, if you think that Age of Empires is just way too difficult and complicated, give this one a try. But having things to do is what makes these games fun. If you played this 12 years ago and are feeling nostalgic or just want to yell at Arkantos's son one more time, go for it. But I don't recommend it for new players."
