,Recommended,266840,28687862,"Posted: 26 December, 2016",all,Aritude,"This is largely the same game you might remember from 2002. However, the Extended Edition and the Tale of the Dragon (Chinese) DLC does add a few new things into the mix.AoM is a game that my friends and I have never really stopped playing. It strikes a sweet spot for multiplayer games, and the original and Titans campaigns are quite masterfully crafted, telling a story that weaves together the mythologies of three very different civilizations. The Chinese campaign is noticeably lower quality, reusing textures and models from other civs instead of using its own. In some places one can ""cheat"" the Chinese campaign AI due to blatant programming oversights. I encountered several AI glitches in the final scenario wherein many enemy units were unresponsive and would just stand there to be obliterated. Nevertheless, it is a fun addition to a very old game.On the multiplayer side, network issues are common, but not as crippling as they were with the original game. In the event that a player is disconnected, the game can usually be saved and reloaded from the same point at which the connection was interrupted. The Tale of the Dragon DLC injects a new life into the multiplayer experience, revitalizing an old game by offering opportunites for new strategies.If you have a group of friends (or even just one friend) who would play with you, this game is a great investment that you'll be coming back to for years to come. It's not perfect, but it is a unique experience that nothing else comes close to."
