,Recommended,266840,14413266,"Posted: 9 February, 2015",all,[BrB] Comrade!,"While their previous titles, Age of Empires I and II, focused on history, Ensemble Studios opted to create a fantastical setting where three factions, the Norse, Ancient Egyptians, and Ancient Greeks collided. Player factions were further divided into three major deities, such as Zeus, Poseidon, and Hades for Greece. Following the footsteps of Starcraft, the three factions were asymmetrical in their playstyles, with the Norse favoring aggressive strategies, the Egyptians favoring late-game power, and the Greeks being middle-of-the-road. Technology paths were further divided by players choosing between two sub-deities at each level of the tech tree. Players could still train historical units like hoplites and pharaohs, but these would be alongside such mythical beasts as chimeras and valkyries. They could even evoke ""God powers,"" with some bringing economic or combat support advantages, while others such as meteor strikes or earthquakes functioning as the game's version of the superweapons of RTS titles from the Command and Conquer series.Like many classic RTS titles, Age of Mythology features multiplayer and singleplayer skirmish modes with various rules as well as a full campaign, which follows the saga of the Atlantean hero, Arkantos. The campaign is actually quite good for an RTS, serving as both tutorial for players as well as providing a classic story of good vs evil, with many familiar figures from all three mythologies along the way. Multiplayer can be done vs other players or even AIs. The Extended Edition also includes content from the original game's Titans expansion, including a 4th faction, the Atlanteans, as well as the campaign. Most importantly a new mechanic, the Titans was introduced for all 4 factions, essentially each faction to construct a super-unit (the eponymous titan) capable of massive destruction.Age of Mythology first came about in the early aughts, alongside such RTS classics as Warcraft III (yes, Warcraft was not always a MMORPG!) and and Rise of Nations. While many later RTS titles would opt for ""real-time tactics"" gameplay as pioneered by the likes of Relic Entertainment's Dawn of War and Company of Heroes titles and Eugen Studios' ""Wargame"" series, Age of Mythology stands as a reminder of the classic RTS formula of ""harvest / build / destroy."""
