,Recommended,266840,13924590,"Posted: 10 January, 2015",all,BadassFreeman,"Picked this up long ago in a sale, when the price finally went down to a decent price. Do I regret buying it? Is it worth picking up? As usual I'll get the bad parts out of the way first, and believe it or not, there are a few here:First and foremost, the price. There's no excuse for this, we're talking about a game that's arround 13 years old (it came out in 2002), and they expect EVERYONE to pay ALMOST 30€!?The f#ck is wrong with you, Microsoft!?I paid arround 6€, and I would pay 10€ MAX. Asking almost 30 for a port is down-right thievery and scamming. Specially when so little effort was put into it...Because yeah, like it or not, this port is lazy. They added Steam Cards, some lazy achievements, and it's Steamworks (or whatever it's called), but that's not enough to put this price on the game. For that price I would expect it to be fully remaked, with new music, textures, models, voices, and more than just one sh#tty new story that was in the official page for ages, and that they didn't even bother to fully translate in all languages. How about A WHOLE NEW RACE, FOR EXAMPLE!? Nah, ♥♥♥♥ that, that would mean put effort into it. I apologize if someone gets offended by this, but Microsoft has been known for being lazy for years and years to come, and things like this won't fix it.Another problem I find with the game are the bugs. I still have the retail version of the game somewhere in my house, with the expansion and all, and I know for a fact that the game had a few bugs... But this? This is near EA-Ubisoft levels. I had my game set on Spanish, mainly for the nostalgia. And you know what the game does? It randomly changes the language of the sounds. Yeah, so fun to be hearing the narrator in Russian when I don't even understand such language. The lighs? They do crazy stuff too! If you look to a hill, the lighs of the lower parts of the map suddenly get so bright, you almost think the sun just exploded. The units? They glitch at times too, getting stuck in weird places, or when being affected by powers, the effects change colors for no reason. For example, Set's summoned units at times change their weird ""Green"" aura when there are too many of them together, and suddenly become pink. I have no idea how is it possible to port an old game that just had a few glitches and make it so it's a Glitch-fest, but they did it.The last problem I had it's not really their fault NOW, but rather when the game was released years ago: The game is insanely easy. I had to put the Hardest difficulty to make the AI haveANY CHANCEduring the original story, to the point that it got boring, and that's an issue that for some reason, it's on a lot of Microsoft games, like Dust; An Elysian Tail. Of course, you wouldn't notice such things when you're arround 8 years old and playing the game for the first time, but come on! Couldn't they fix the difficulty and AI? Their main problem is that, even if they're way more powerful than you, they're scared and won't fight unless they can DESTROY THE LIVING CRAP OUT OF YOU WITHOUT EFFORT. I have even tested it, alone vs 11 other bots. It took them arround 20 minutes to destroy me. I REPEAT, ALONE AGAINST 11 BOTS. That's just pathetic.All of that being said, does the game have good stuff? You bet your #ss! The game is quite well-balanced (Well, the Expansion race might be a bit too powerful on my opinion), with each race working in complete different ways (in contrast with Age of Empires, where it's hard to spot that many differences from one race to another): The Greek are the ""balanced"" race, having expensive but powerful troops, the Egyptians being more focused in economy and defense while also being able to swarm with cheap troops, the Nords being the most offensive race with little defensive stuff and building with the soldiers, and the Atlanteans, who can turn any of their troops into heroes, and can use their powers more than once. Each race also has their own Titans, but they act exactly the same, and that's kind of a let-down.Multiplayer is where this game shines, like it happend with Age of Empires. Matches feel fair, there are quite a lot of maps to play, with also randomly generated ones. The map editor? I've already seen some beautiful stuff on it, though I haven't personally tried any map with friends yet. Matches sure as hell can take too long at times if the players are too passive (you know, the classic p#ssy that only focuses on the economy for like, 30 minutes until he Steam-rolls everyone), but fairly enough that's why the Nords exist, they attack other players fast and can even hold their own in Late-game with sick powers like the Ragnarok. The only part about this that I don't like, are maps with water. Dunno if it's just me, but I hate fighting with ships, it's just boring.The story-mode, even while extremely easy, can be entertaining. The story line has some clichés but it's both decent ANDEDUCATIONAL! HOLY MOTHER OF F#CK, you learn a lot of Mythology with this game! Back when I played this in 2002-2003, I was really interested in the old times, and that's one of the reason why I liked this game: It's just like those dumbf#cks of the old times though the real world was: With weird messed up creatures everywhere, Gods among men and all that crap. You can even pause the game to check the Lore of each unit on the game, something that can be fun if you're actually interested in story, like me.Is the game worth it? Yeah. But not at this crazy price. Wait for a good sale, and if possible, have a friend to play with. I'd say the game is worth picking at arround 10€, NOT MORE. If it goes even lower, then you should probably Wololo your own balls and commit sudoku.Oh and, please: If you even play online, don't be one of those Casuals who just focus on the Economy for half an hour. If you do so, don't just ragequit when the nords blow you up, FIGHT LIKE IF YOU HAD ANY BALLS, DAMN IT!"
