76561198062937021,Recommended,266840,10136774,"Posted: 16 May, 2014",all,LeoTF,"Age of Mythology is a great little RTS. Simple enough for kids to pick up and play and just about complex enough for RTS veterans to enjoy weaving intricate strategies and balancing resource spending.The campaigns are a nice little feature, so far as pre-set RTS scenarios go, they're enjoyable enough. (Though you'll probably only play through them once, admittedly.) The main meat of the game comes in online multiplayer and offline 'random maps' (which actually aren't that random. You can choose the map, your opponents and just about everything else.) where you're pitted against another player or a (surprisingly decent) AI to fight in a number of gamemodes. The variety in gamemodes is only about five choices, and these gamemodes pretty much all boil down to ""Destroy the enemy!"" but they're fun nonetheless, and the wide selection of maps (enhanced even further by Steam workshop integration) and gods to choose from make for a much more varied and replayable game than may appear at first glance.Be aware though, players of the original AoM in particular. The amount of HD'ing and upscaling means this game takes more to run than you might be expecting. Early glitches and issues are being resolved quickly, and I've personally seen my game performance improve over the past few weeks thanks to patches from the devs.If I'm honest, I can't truly say that I'd be willing to pay £23 for this. It IS a fun game with all its expansions, but it's an old and comparatively simple one and £23 just seems too much to me.However, if you're like me and loved it as a kid, the £23 price tag isn't too much for the nostalgia hit.Everyone else, if it drops to around £15 or lower, I'd highly recommend buying it."
