76561198104175526,Recommended,266840,30052392,Posted: 19 February,all,Bandageboy877,"(SPOILER FREE) As a person who has played the titans expansion and the original game on disk form for years I did not expect a new expansion in Chinese mythology and wanted to explore these new features. When I booted up the game I scouted the main menu and stumbled upon all mythology tutorials as well as 4 campaigns in total, two of which I had not seen before. I have played new Chinese side and have come to a conclusion on all five religions. Greeks are best for beginners, well rounded and easiest to use. Egyptians are harder to use but are the beat for seige and guerilla warfare tactics. The Norse are for the more barbarian natures, but are no less fun. Best for hiding and annoying others with hit and run tactics. The atlantean armies have the most heroes, and their armies are the hardest to use. Until the Chinese came. They use the most confusing mix of units but for someone who underatands them they can be a force to be feared.Anyone who wants to play, buy the game with a group of friends and let them know what you are made of."
,Recommended,266840,30053706,Posted: 20 February,all,Takeda Iesyu,"When Ensemble made the transition from 2D to 3D, they jumped it with this game: a ""what-if"" scenario where gods can actively intercede on their worshippers' behalf. SkyBox came along and remastered it, adding a few bits here and there to make it work better on modern machines. And it is awesome!PROS:+Like many of the Age of Empires games, this one is easy to learn, but difficult to master. There's a lot of potential for nearly any kind of RTS strategy.+Each of the four different factions has its own unique playstyle. The Greeks are a comprehensive, vanilla faction for understanding the games' more complex mechanics, the Norse are better-suited to rushers and highly combative players, the Egyptians are excellent at defensive gameplay, and the Atlanteans are very noob-friendly, easy to learn for first-time visitors to the RTS genre.+The game has a number of combat triangles, from the Infantry/Cavalry/Archers to the Human/Myth Unit/Hero to the Arrow Ship/Hammer Ship/Siege Ship.+There are a number of resources to manage collection, especially for building different types of armies (ie prodominantly cavalry).+Game introduces God Powers, similar to abilities in MOBAS. These can change the game at a critical moment by various means (ie burning down a forest the enemy was using as part of their wall, earthquaking their fortresses, or forcing a caesefire for a minute).+Game introduces myth units and heroes, each of which have their own different special abilities to give them an edge over their enemies.+Instead of researching new ages of technology, you pick new gods to worship, each giving their own unique units, god powers, and bonuses to compliment your playstyle.+Multiple different ways to play, from rushing to turtling to building a wonder. Each is viable in its own way.+Surprisingly good soundtrack, and decent enough sound effects.+Main campaign (Fall of the Trident) is surprisingly fun to play through.+Mods!+Map editor! (Impressively comprehensive and can be used to make some seriously cool things).+Audio taunts!+Extended Edition remasters the graphics to look far better than they once did, including the option for a day/night cycle, AA, shadows, and improved water.+Extended Edition also offers Achievements, Trading Cards, and Twitch Integration.+Extended Edition offers a few new maps and a new option to disable Titans (wheras before, the normal strategy for winning games was rushing to build a titan before your opponent).+Access to online play again, including ranked play!CONS-Second and third campaigns (Atlantis Reborn and The Golden Gift) are very lacking The former appears to only exist to showcase the new faction while the latter feels like a fanmade project thrown up after a few days' work.-Audiotaunt spam (especially 999 taunt) can get annoying.-Frequent lag when playing with friends (for me, this only exists for about 2-3 minutes before going away).-I've heard of many people being unable to launch the game. I've never had this issue.By itself, Age of Mythology: Extended Edition is a great game to play. If you don't have it (or the original), or love the RTS genre, I'd strongly recommend it. If you do have the original, I'd more cautiously recommend it, mainly if it was on sale. While there are a number of improvements, they aren't substantial enough to warrant purchase for their own sake."
